.",[17,18,19],"React","Go","gRPC","https://www.google.com","yahoo.com","/projects/aether-cloud","hello","src/content/projects/aether-cloud.mdx","91221c414eee21cb","aether-cloud.mdx",true,"distributed-monitor",{"id":28,"data":30,"body":37,"filePath":38,"digest":39,"legacyId":40,"deferredRender":27},{"id":28,"title":31,"description":32,"tags":33,"image":34,"liveUrl":35,"codeUrl":21,"readMoreUrl":36},"Distributed Systems Monitor","Real-time visualization tool for monitoring microservices architecture health and latency. Provides deep insights into network traffic and service dependencies.",[18,17,19],"data:image/jpeg;base64,","google.com","/projects/distributed-monitor","helol","src/content/projects/distributed-monitor.mdx","9edc1f8897981ce6","distributed-monitor.mdx","blog",["Map",43,44,53,54,63,64,73,74,83,84,92,93,104,105],"design-system",{"id":43,"data":45,"filePath":50,"digest":51,"legacyId":52,"deferredRender":27},{"id":43,"title":46,"description":47,"date":48,"category":49},"Building a Custom Design System with Tailwind","How we scaled our internal component library by embracing utility classes and strict design tokens.","Jun 02, 2023","Development","src/content/blog/design-system.mdx","3c4f2857f74c2d09","design-system.mdx","eng-manager",{"id":53,"data":55,"filePath":60,"digest":61,"legacyId":62,"deferredRender":27},{"id":53,"title":56,"description":57,"date":58,"category":59},"The Engineering Manager’s Reading List","A curated collection of books that shaped my approach to leadership, team dynamics, and technical decision making.","Jul 15, 2023","Career","src/content/blog/eng-manager.mdx","712539041c505a9e","eng-manager.mdx","minimal-ui",{"id":63,"data":65,"filePath":70,"digest":71,"legacyId":72,"deferredRender":27},{"id":63,"title":66,"description":67,"date":68,"category":69},"The Case for Minimalist User Interfaces","Exploring the psychological benefits of reduced visual noise and how to design content-first experiences that respect user attention.","Sep 12, 2023","Design","src/content/blog/minimal-ui.mdx","6b6bcce12d0029fb","minimal-ui.mdx","test",{"id":73,"data":75,"body":79,"filePath":80,"digest":81,"legacyId":82,"deferredRender":27},{"id":73,"title":76,"description":77,"date":78,"category":73},"Designing Quiet Software","On building systems that do their work without demanding attention.","Aug 30, 2023","![Abstract dark minimal architecture](/AASTU.png)\r\n\r\nSoftware doesn’t need to announce itself.\r\n\r\nThe best systems I’ve worked on are the ones users barely notice —\r\nthey load quickly, respond instantly, and never make you think about\r\nwhat’s happening underneath.\r\n\r\nThis is what I think of as **quiet architecture**.\r\n\r\n## Structure Before Features\r\n\r\nBefore adding animations, state management layers, or abstractions,\r\nI try to answer one question:\r\n\r\n> What is the simplest structure that will still scale?\r\n\r\nFor example, when building a blog with Astro, you don’t need a database\r\nif your content is mostly static.\r\n\r\n```ts\r\n// src/content/config.ts\r\nimport { defineCollection, z } from \"astro:content\";\r\n\r\nconst blog = defineCollection({\r\n  schema: z.object({\r\n    title: z.string(),\r\n    description: z.string(),\r\n    pubDate: z.date(),\r\n    tags: z.array(z.string()),\r\n  }),\r\n});\r\n\r\nexport const collections = { blog };\r\n```","src/content/blog/test.mdx","5ac1ab799240f6d7","test.mdx","dist-state",{"id":83,"data":85,"filePath":89,"digest":90,"legacyId":91,"deferredRender":27},{"id":83,"title":86,"description":87,"date":88,"category":49},"Understanding Distributed State Management","A deep dive into why managing state across micro-frontends is challenging and how to solve it using event-driven architectures.","Oct 24, 2023","src/content/blog/dist-state.mdx","81d9f3a27752e84d","dist-state.mdx","type-safe-events",{"id":92,"data":94,"body":100,"filePath":101,"digest":102,"legacyId":103,"deferredRender":27},{"id":92,"title":95,"description":96,"date":97,"category":98,"readTime":99},"Designing Type-Safe Event Architectures with TypeScript","When building large-scale distributed systems, the communication between services often becomes the bottleneck...","Nov 12, 2024","Engineering","12 min read","When building large-scale distributed systems, the communication between services often becomes the bottleneck for both performance and developer velocity. While REST APIs offer a familiar pattern, they frequently lead to tight coupling and the \"distributed monolith\" anti-pattern.\n\nThe shift toward event-driven architecture (EDA) promises decoupled components, but it often comes at the cost of visibility and type safety. How do we ensure that a producer's payload matches the consumer's expectations without manual schema registries?\n\n## Defining the Schema\n\nWe can leverage TypeScript's advanced type system to create a central truth for our events. By using discriminated unions, we can ensure that every event handler is exhaustive and type-safe.","src/content/blog/type-safe-events.mdx","47539937429c44d8","type-safe-events.mdx","perf-nextjs",{"id":104,"data":106,"filePath":110,"digest":111,"legacyId":112,"deferredRender":27},{"id":104,"title":107,"description":108,"date":78,"category":109},"Performance Optimization in Next.js 14","Leveraging the latest features in the App Router to achieve sub-second page loads and perfect Lighthouse scores.","Infrastructure","src/content/blog/perf-nextjs.mdx","e859c646ccb0f84f","perf-nextjs.mdx"]